You cannot fix a network if the machine itself won't turn on. Having built a strong foundation in command-line diagnostics, I am stepping away from the terminal for this log 
to focus entirely on the physical side of IT: diagnosing, troubleshooting, and repairing Physical Hardware.

CORE INTERNAL COMPONENTS
  CPU (Central Processing Unit): The CPU is one of the most integral pieces to the build and often has the same issues occur, typically involving: Heat, Power, and Contact.
    Heat: Modern CPUs have safety measures built into them called 'Thermal Throttling' that intentionally slows it down to generate less heat after reaching a certain temperature 
    (Typically between 90-100 degrees Celsius or 194-212 degrees Farenheit). If the CPU hits its T-Junction limit, it will shut down automatically to avoid melting.
